<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&gt; It’s nice to see a discussion on Orion’s feasibility, but this discussion has more flame than fact. Everyone stop blaming each other for being biased, one sided, lemming brained and other stuff.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
I like to think I've not flamed anybody. I've attacked the idea that butchering the scientific method to suit your own views is antithetical to logical study of a subject.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&gt; I seriously doubt that the team behind Orion would somehow forget to see if the pusher-plates would survive the torture from the nuclear pulse units.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
I doubt that it's a vast conspiracy which says that they didn't consider this issue very carefully and then supposedly hid the unfavorable results of their studies.<br>
The issue here in this thread boils down to a question of whether the favorable reporting of Orion we relate to readers is fraudulent, and NASA actually pounded the nails into the coffin of Orion's feasibility in the '60s.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&gt; I don’t have access to a nuke so that I could test it, but I think it would be possible for me, to get hold of some software that would simulate it.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
G.Dyson reported in the &quot;Orion lemming's Bible&quot; that later generations of the same software they used in the '60s is in use today in industrial applications. I don't urge people to read the book to give money to G.Dyson (I've read most of it standing up in bookstores). He includes extensive bibliography notes and other things which could be used to follow up on stuff reported in the book. Not fiction or cartoons but real govpubs and technical articles.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&gt; I think the Orion is possible, but I don’t think it’s practical... There are other ways into space, all of whom requires nuclear power in some form to be practical, like the space elevator and ion-drives.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Several points:<br>
If beanstalks or tethers or hypersonic skyhooks come along, fine. They don't help us get big payloads to the planets quickly.<br>
Ion won't get you into space. It will get you around space, but Orion does it before your crew dies of old age... Chemicals also are of some limited use in the inner solar system, but long-duration exposure does harm, somewhat less than ion drive.<br>
 You won't use ion drive for crewed missions. NPR gets them there (with vast amounts of the starting mass being cargo &amp; safeties) while the ion driven ship is slowly speeding up to gradually get into its trans-Mars interplanetary trajectory.<br>
<br>
If you've got the political will to use NTR or even nuclear-powered VASIMR, then you can use NPR with a bit of international cooperation. VASIMR, ICAN and Daedalus require new breakthroughs, and smaller innovation gets Orion type NPR flying sooner.<br>
<br>
I don't necessarily urge using Orion for launch from the ground, unless it's proven that a later generation version is clean &amp; safe.<br>
 Many points against it here: political palatability -even if clean- safety &amp; reliability of the firing mechanisms &amp; bombs in the hectic &amp; hazardous launch environment, etc.<br>
There are big differences between launch and interplanetary space travel requirements. Many things work for launch, including perfectly clean &amp; well known H/O rockets.<br>
Few things as well known work well in space; It takes ~8km/sec to get to orbit, and <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">50</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->km/sec to get to Mars in 6 weeks, and only NPR does this, and only Orion is workable now, with readily understood technology. No containment or channeling of fusing plasma, no containment of antiprotons, no new inventions.<br>
Read the NASA MSFC paper on EPPP, and pay particular attention to their comments on the &quot;mark-1&quot; 10 meter ship. Lift its parts to HEO with STS or Energia HLVs, and we've got a great interplanetary ship -<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>now</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->. Probably cost less to start this program than they're spending now keeping the Shuttle orbiter Death-Traps flying.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&gt; Let's just keep the Orion where it is and let it die along with all of the 50's imageneering. It's a nice dream, but there are better dreams.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Better dreams for interplanetary travel which allow rapid robust routine &amp; safe travel among the Solar system, using technology readily understood in the '50s and '60s, and even more useful &amp; cost effective today?<br>
<br>
Tim1965<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&gt; There are better methods of nuclear propulsion that can be used other then orion: such ion drives, plasma drives, Deadalas class fusion microexplosion drives, and antimatter- matter annhilation powered drives et el.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
 Like I've said before, There are a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>few</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> other proposals which might equal Orion's preformance (only a very few), but with Orion, the greatest technical hurdles are akin to innovating a grease-mist-sprayer to cover a 10 or 40 meter plate in between 1 per 20 second &gt;=20KT pulses. They planned to use the compression of the shocks to generate steam to run generator turbines, cycle the loading mechanism, eject the bombs, and pump the sprayer.<br>
Propellant for the bombs for the return trip (~60% of the return trip bombs mass) is made either from in-situ materials (ices), or even the crew's own biological wastes...<br>
 Tell me there are better options than this one, which uses up tons of weapons-grade fissionables, and even more tons of sh!t<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :b --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":b"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
